Bosses of Bloodborne [PART 1]. After a long and arduous semester, Iâ€™m finally getting around to writing Bloodborne content for this blog. Letâ€™s just get started without any further delay! For each boss in the game, Iâ€™ll share both my first impressions and my later reflections. The former is pretty self-explanatory; the latter can range from atmosphere to design to hard mechanics â€“ whatever strikes me most strongly. Iâ€™ll try, as I usually do, to keep it varied and interesting. For the sake of tidiness and convenience, Iâ€™ve relegated everything to beneath the Moon. This first post will discuss Vicar Amelia and all bosses that can be fought prior to her, with the exception of Darkbeast Paarl. Enjoy! Cleric Beast My first foray against the Cleric Beast was actually pretty disappointing, though I was very impressed by the aesthetic design of the boss and the bridge arena. I defeated the Cleric Beast in my first attempt â€“ and though I attribute some of my success to skill and planning, a good portion of it was due to the fact that the boss hardly knew what it was doing. The Cleric Beast just floundered about for most of the fight, swiping at walls and obstacles more than it ever attempted to hit me. Once it just decided to leap to the far end of the bridge, away from my character. The poor thing just seemed bewildered and confused. I suspect now that this odd behavior was caused by the memory leak glitch that affected the game prior to patch 1.03, but it was pretty funny at the time. Now, having fought the Cleric Beast as it was meant to be fought, I rather like this fight. Itâ€™s large and intimidating, itâ€™s iconic, itâ€™s just aggressive enough for new players, and it imparts a sense that all is not impossible. Overall, itâ€™s a great introduction to the combat of Bloodborne. Moreover, the fact that itâ€™s optional allows more seasoned players, who wouldnâ€™t benefit from this fight in the same way that new players do, to skip amateur hour and cut straight to Father Gascoigne. Father Gascoigne My immediate impression of Father Gascoigne â€“ which subsequent playthroughs have only strengthened â€“ was that the good reverend marked a return to the tight, straightforward combat that characterized most of the humanoid bosses in the first Dark Souls. He kept me on my toes the entire time, especially since I neglected to use the music box during my first fights against him. I had collected it from his daughter, but for whatever reason I forgot to use it during combat. Adrenaline, I suppose. Piecing his story together posthumously was one of my favorite parts of Bloodborne. Unlike many other Souls bosses â€“ who are built up and hinted toward well before the fight itself â€“ Gascoigne is fought at a point when not much information is available to the player. Not even the Healing Church is very well known at this time. Piecing Gascoigneâ€™s life story together is something like a forensic investigation â€“ and it happens over the course of the entire game, so that the player really feels the weight of what he/she did well after he/she killed Father Gascoigne. Itâ€™s not like Astraea, who assaults the player with guilt during the fight itself, or Artorias, whose reputation is built up so high only to be subverted. Here, the playerâ€™s emotional understanding of this (initially) very frustrating boss changes after he/she has vented all of that frustration on him, and felt good doing so. Just when you thought that you had figured out every branch of their plotline, Gascoigne and his family once make you feel the weight of your own ignorance. And so the boss fight continues to be emotionally impactful even towards the end of the game. Blood-Starved Beast Before I learned its moveset, fighting the Blood-Starved Beast was one of the most frantic and bewildering boss fights that Iâ€™ve run across in a Souls game. I never found the boss particularly difficult or frustrating, but VERY frantic and fast-paced. Watching that thing leap around just aboutï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ gave me a heart attack! It was probably the first boss that forced me into the aggressive mentality that Miyazaki and FromSoftware wanted to encourage with Bloodborne. Not much to say beyond that, really. I do, however, like the implication that this beastâ€™s blood was drained as part of an attempted chalice ritual. The poison status effect might initially seem like a tacked-on gimmick, and it felt so at first â€“ but Iâ€™ve since realized the sheer brilliance of it, in the scheme of the gameâ€™s overall design. Prior to this point in the game, itâ€™s feasible that the player could have used blood vials and the regain system to squeeze by without having cultivated a good sense of dodging and timing. The slow poison effect puts an end to all that. Here, as Bloodborne enters the pace that it will maintain for most of the game, it forces players to learn a core skill that they will need in all future areas â€“ because if they donâ€™t, theyâ€™ll die from poison inflicted by telegraphed combos and glancing blows that could easily have been avoided. The Witch(es) of Hemwick I visited Hemwick after defeating Amelia, actually. In fact, in my first playthrough, I did absolutely nothing between the Blood-Starved Beast and Vicar Amelia â€“ but Iâ€™ll save the details for that bossâ€™s entry. Anyway! The Witches of Hemwick felt like a pleasant blend of the Foolâ€™s Idol, Pinwheel, and Dark Sun Gwyndolin. Theyâ€™re a fun â€œpuzzle boss,â€ with creative use of additional enemies. Not once did I feel frustrated while fighting this dual boss, despite the fact that I died twice to them, because it was interesting. It followed a principle that was largely ignored by the Dark Souls II team â€“ that when multiple enemies comprise a boss fight, those enemiesâ€™ respective designs and AIs should be made specifically to complement the other enemies in the boss arena. I also appreciate that, like Pinwheel, the Witches of Hemwick guard a near-necessary component of character/game progression â€“ and so theyâ€™re not difficult in any straightforward sense. Vicar Amelia Oh, Ameliaâ€¦ The first time I defeated her, it was with a +3 Threaded Cane, rather low Vitality, and 30+ deaths under my belt. Vicar Amelia was the first boss in Bloodborne to stop me dead in my tracks â€“ and it was largely my own doing. Prior to my first serious attempt at killing her, I had explored the area to the right of the Grand Cathedral. After several long and arduous fights, leading to a confusing dead-end, I assumed that the areas to the side of the Grand Cathedral were meant for a later time. So I did not visit Hemwick, nor did I acquire any of the vital blood echoes and upgrade materials to be gained there. The result was a frustrating slog against this hideous poodle-deer, in which I could whittle her down to her last eighth of health reliably and consistently â€“ but would inevitably fail when a glancing blow stunlocked me into a deadly combo, or when her healing undid all of my hard work. Out of pride, I did the equivalent of demolishing a brick wall by repeatedly smashing my head against it. There was no dignity in my victory, but there was much joy. Now, having learned a better route for character progression, Amelia is one of the easiest bosses for me to defeat; I take pleasure in cutting her down. I can appreciate how Amelia requires the player to use nearly all of the skills that had been cultivated one-at-a-time through other bosses. I can also appreciate how the fight against her rewards the player for taking a varied approach, dealing near-equal damage to each of her body parts. And I can also appreciate from firsthand experience what an obnoxious, repulsive bitch she is â€“ â€œbitchâ€ here meaning â€œugly female dogâ€ as much as it means â€œenormous pain in my ass.â€

Feelinâ€™ kinda crappy? Do these five things today. By Alice Nicholls We all go through times in our lives when life doesnâ€™t go the way we expected. Events or situations throw us in the deep end and we find ourselves in situations that we canâ€™t actually change but that make us feel â€¦ crappy.ï¿½ï¿½ Perhaps this has to do with work. Or maybe you have a few days in a row where you had big plans and you get sick so youâ€™re forced to take time off. Maybe you budgeted for something thatâ€™s become more expensive and you have to put some things on the back-burner. These are all situations that are out of our control, yet they can send even the happiest people around the bend and bring on negative emotions. If the situation itself canâ€™t be controlled, then why do we feel crappy about it? Itâ€™s the way that your mind reacts to it â€“ or rather â€“ the way your subconscious thought pattern â€˜tellsâ€™ you to react. With exasperation, frustration, anger or hopelessness. If you can become more conscious, then you can change the way you relate to a situation and that will change the outcome of something you would have perceived as negative to something that beings welcome surrender, feels calm or simply â€˜meant to beâ€™. It is what it is. When we are overcome by our attachment to an idea we have in our minds about what things are supposed to be like, we spend a lot of time dwelling on the past or living with the future in mind and this does little for our state of fulfillment in the now. â€œThe true definition of mental illness is when the majority of your time is spent in the past or future, but rarely living in the realism of NOW.â€ How though, do we change the way we see things in our minds to make the days we live happier? Hereâ€™s four easy ways. 1. Recognise the emotion. Instead of sinking into the pits of â€˜should have, could have, would haveâ€™â€¦ be conscious of what it is youâ€™re feeling. Is it despair, anger, frustration or loneliness? The emotion is there for a reason, even if it is created by the mind. Give it a little room to be â€¦ feel it. We rarely, if ever, give our emotions a place to be recognised before we push them down and pretend they donâ€™t exist. How many times has someone asked you what was wrong, only for you to say â€˜nothingâ€™, even though there are 15 things getting you down. Own the emotion and it is much easier to send that baby flying away.ï¿½ï¿½ 2. Make a conscious decision to wave goodbye to that emotion, itâ€™s fleeting. Only you can make the decision to wallow in it â€“ the emotion itself doesnâ€™t make the choice to stay, you have the responsibility of control over it. Picture a baby who cries for an instant over a toy being snatched away. Is that baby still upset about it an hour later? No. A baby probably isnâ€™t too fazed about losing the toy even three minutes later. We forget to live in the moment like a child does and this is something weâ€™d be much better off doing. 3. Talk yourself through it. With pushing our emotions under the rug comes a constant habit of deafening our ears to our own voice. Many people today whoâ€™re dwelling in the past or existing only thinking about the future donâ€™t have a good relationship with themselves. An excellent way of dealing with set-backs is to have a quick reality â€˜check-inâ€™ with yourself. Phrases like â€œwill my worrying change the future?â€, â€œeverything will work out as it needs toâ€, â€œWhat is this lesson here to teach me?â€ or â€œthings are as they should beâ€ will help you to relax and surrender in crappy situations. 4. Become comfortable with uncertainty. As adults we hold onto negative emotions as if they will comfort us, and then many of us feel secure or safe feeling crappy because weâ€™ve identified with that feeling for so long. Itâ€™s time to give yourself permission to be okay with uncertainty. The better you can respond to uncertainty in life the more opportunity you have to feel fulfilled because guess what? Life is never certain and we simply canâ€™t control everything. 5. Breathe. How many times in our lives do things happen out of our control and we go from whoa to CRAZY in .2 seconds flat? Unleashing fury and vitriol or helpless anxiety reaction over ourselves or anybody around us. And the one thing we forgot to do is breathe. Giving ourselves a small pocket of breath allows us to calm any instant negative reaction and follow the steps above. An excellent breathing technique that calms nerves and reduces physical and emotional pain is the following. Try it today in a moment of stress or anxiety. A slow count of four while breathing in, then count of four holding the breath. Then a slow count of four breathing out out and hold the breath out for four seconds and repeat. Whatâ€™s left? A calmer, happier person who can roll with the ebbs and flows of life with peace, purpose and a strong belief that they are right where they should be. I watched the editorsâ€™ fingers whiz across the keyboard, making drastic changes in a matter of moments. â€œI could totally do this,â€ I thought to myself. â€œI could go to SVA for this.â€ Five years later, Iâ€™m now a third-year film student at SVA and could not be happier with my choices. ï¿½ï¿½Iâ€™ve been lucky enough to form relationships with several teachers whom I deeply admire, as well as some really wonderful colleagues who keep me inspired. ï¿½ï¿½I work in the schoolâ€™s Avid computer lab, assisting students who are editing their projects, helping sort out any technical problems. Iâ€™ve also been interning for a year and a half at a commercial editing house, Beast Editorial. I truthfully donâ€™t know where I would be in life had I not enrolled at SVA. The Greatest Generation is the long-awaited head-on collision. The title emerges out of what lyricist Dan Campbell does best: reference. He stares at the sky, afraidï¿½ï¿½â€œlike a kid in the sixties/staring at the sky/waiting for the bomb to fall,â€ compares President Trumanâ€™s atomic legacy to his own shameful â€œfuckups,â€ and travels back in time with his anxieties to â€œ1929â€¦ on the verge of a great collapse.â€ He even directly references grandparents when the whole world smells like his grandmotherâ€™s favorite brand of cigarettes inï¿½ï¿½â€œWe Could Die Like Thisâ€ (though it isnâ€™t complete without Coppertone)ï¿½ï¿½or in the slurry of anger and regret that drips from his grandfatherâ€™s unofficial eulogy,ï¿½ï¿½â€œThe Devil In My Bloodstream.â€ Campbell is a resourceful writer, adding these elements to the lyrical motifs (conjured ghosts, pill bottles, shaking hands) that pull the album together even further. Even when Campbell is referencing his older work (â€I was kind of hoping youâ€™d stay,â€ he concludes onï¿½ï¿½â€œPassing Through A Screen Door,â€ the first of several references to the two previous Wonder Years outings), the album is too grounded in itself to ever feel as if it canâ€™t support its own personal theme of trying to find the silver lining of the looming black clouds on its own. All these feats of writing, however, could have easily fallen flatter than they did were it not for the bandâ€™s truly remarkable musicianship backing Campbell every step of the way. Objective analysis reveals this to be true time and time again.ï¿½ï¿½â€œJesus Christ, did I fuck up?â€ wouldnâ€™t have hit nearly as hard if Campbell hadnâ€™t been screaming it during the incredibly well-built bridge that climaxes around it in â€œPassing Through A Screen Door.â€ï¿½ï¿½â€œI know how it feels to be at war with a world that never loved meâ€ from â€œThe Devil In My Bloodstreamâ€ seems like a predictable choice for a text-based tattoo, but that doesnâ€™t seem to matter as much when it sounds like Campbellâ€™s drowning breath in the catharsis of the songâ€™s second half, finally succumbing by the end of it. Theï¿½ï¿½â€œwhoa-whoaâ€â€™s inï¿½ï¿½â€œA Radiance in Trafficâ€ are a pop-punk cliche, but here they legitimately sound like the onomatopoeia of explosions when they rest above the vicious cymbal crashes, towering guitars, and anchor of the bass line. FIFA scandal reverberating across soccer-crazy South America. BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) â€” Within hours of the FIFA scandal breaking, Sergio Jadue, the president of Chileâ€™s soccer federation, was declaring his innocence even though he wasnâ€™t formally accused of anything. Jadue was referring to a part of Wednesdayâ€™s sweeping U.S. Justice Department indictments that, without specifying them by name, said the 10 presidents of the South American Football Confederation were to receive bribes from a company called Datisa in exchange for transmission rights to games of the Copa America, the tournament of the continentâ€™s national teams. Jadue said $1.5 million was indeed transferred in late 2013 from the confederation, known as CONMEBOL, but it was an advance on a contract for Copa America. â€œI donâ€™t even have to be worried,â€ Jadue told La Tercera newspaper from Switzerland, where he attended a FIFA meeting. â€œThis wonâ€™t affect at all the work of the federation or its president.â€ Itâ€™s hard to imagine that anything will be business as usual when it comes to soccer here. The FIFA investigations are having a ripple effect across soccer-crazy South America, whose teams have won nine World Cups and where national squads are preparing for the continental tournament that starts in two weeks. Governments of powerhouses Argentina and Brazil, which for years looked the other way amid rumblings of corruption at various levels of the â€œbeautiful game,â€ are launching investigations. And powerbrokers such as Paraguayan Nicolas Leoz, former president of CONMEBOL, are on the defensive. The 86-year-old defiantly declared his innocence from a hospital as Paraguay processes a U.S. extradition request. â€œWe are looking at a game that has been mismanaged for so long, and so many were implicit,â€ said Christopher Gaffney, author of â€œTemples of the Earthbound Gods,â€ a look at the history of soccer in Argentina and Brazil. â€œOnce you start pulling on the strings, the whole thing could start to unravel.â€ In Argentina, prosecutors have charged three men implicated in the scandal with tax fraud, racketeering and money laundering for their involvement. The Federal Administration for Public Revenue charged Alejandro Burzaco, president of the sports marketing company Torneos y Competencias, and Mariano and Hugo Jinkis, owners of the sports media business Full Play. All were named Wednesday in a U.S. indictment saying they bribed soccer officials in exchange for the rights to international tournaments. The United States has requested their extradition. Both Jinkins were in Argentina, their lawyer Jorge Anzorreguy said, but had not turned themselves in. Burzacoâ€™s whereabouts were unknown. Cabinet chief Anibal Fernandez said authorities would look closely at the companies to see if tax evasion went beyond the three men. The scandal has quickly changed things in Argentine soccer. Before his death last year, Julio Grondona was seen as the right hand of FIFA president Joseph Blatter and head of the national football association. Called the â€œmonje negro,â€ or â€œblack monk,â€ because of his reputation of making FIFA decisions behind the scenes, Grondona would surely have been under the microscope of U.S. prosecutors. On Friday, Argentina voted against Blatter, who was re-elected easily. â€œBeyond the initial commotion, every time you open a can of worms it means something positive for the future,â€ said Mariano Berges, a former judge who helped form the Buenos Aires-based group â€œLetâ€™s Save Football.â€ Berges said that it would have been nearly impossible for such an investigation to begin in Argentina, where similar to many countries in the region, top politicians and businessmen are heavily involved in the sport. â€œComing from the United States, itâ€™s more acceptable,â€ said Berges. In Brazil, Justice Minister Jose Eduardo Cardozo said authorities were studying the indictments to see where or how Brazilian businessmen and soccer executives might have committed crimes. Rio de Janeiro-based Klefer Sports Marketing company had to turn over documents related to its contract with the Brazilian soccer confederation for marketing rights to the domestic soccer championship. Klefer signed the contract together with Traffic, a Brazilian sports marketing company that American officials are investigating. Klefer has denied any wrongdoing. In Rio de Janeiro, the Brazilian confederation ordered the removal of the name of Jose Maria Marin from its lavish building. The 83-year-old Marin was one of 14 senior sports officials and marketing executives charged in the FIFA investigation. He was arrested in Zurich. On Thursday, the Brazilian Senate approved the request made by former soccer star and now Senator Romario for a congressional panel to investigate corruption in soccer. In Uruguay, newspapers were filled with accounts claiming corrupt dealings by former CONMEBOL president Eugenio Figueredo. He was already being investigated in Uruguay for irregularities during his long tenure as CONMEBOL vice president. In a continent where many are often skeptical of U.S. involvement in local affairs, governments appeared eager to work with American investigators. Although no Colombian national was named in the indictments, the countryâ€™s attorney general said investigators would review the international financial transactions of top soccer officials. If irregularities are found, Colombia â€œwould be very interested in going forward with an investigation that fits within the macro investigation of the United States and Switzerland,â€ said Attorney General Eduardo Montealegre. _______ Associated Press writers Almudena Calatrava in Buenos Aires, Leonardo Haberkorn in Montevideo, Uruguay, Eva Vergara and Luis Andres Henao in Santiago, Chile, Adriana Gomez Licon in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and Jairo Anchique in Bogota, Colombia, contributed to this report.

Collaborator Feature: Adam Lee. Adam Lee is a Telecom Student at Indiana University working primarily within student film productions and also freelance photography/videography. My first interactions with Adam Lee were quite pleasant. Nick and I were over at the coop playing some mellow jams with Neal Anderson and Joe Klatt from Patchwork, sipping on wine, laughing at terrible puns. As we digressed, Adam joined us, snapped some photos, promised to email them later. Well.. we never got themâ€¦ ehhhhrmmâ€¦ but that didnâ€™t damage the interaction! Heâ€™s a great guy:) The Homestead Session Confessional Jump forward like 3 months. Itâ€™s the night before our long anticipated video shoot. Weâ€™re sweating, pulling our hairs out. Our videographer just canceled. Sick. In a last-ditch effort to jettison anxiety, we join local musicians Charlie Jesseph and Peter Oren at Runcible for half-price pitchers. Through course of conversation, we remembered our friend Adam Lee and his background in telecommunications. After a quick call and some coordinating, we had our savior! Adam Lee, Adam Lee, ADAM LEE! (chanting dies out, cut, queue video) We are truly indebted to Adam for making this shoot a reality. He skipped a class, checked out about $100k worth of IU equipment from the telecom building, acquired a friend, Bryce Ferendo, to assist, and worked some magic! Alongside good friend and sound engineer Kyle Hoopt, we shot three videos in a span of a few hours, a session we are calling the Homestead Sessions. You can view all three videos from the Homestead Sessions on YouTube, as well as download the audio files FOR FREE on bandcamp. We recently caught back up with Adam Lee via the webs and sent him some questions to fill us in and thus fill you in! He elaborates on favorite gear, his goals, his approach to filmingâ€¦ Itâ€™s all below! Enjoy:) Q & A How do you know Nick and Jake? I know Nick and Jake because they have come by and played at my co-op. What is your goal as a videographer and/or as a telecom student? My ultimate goal is to be a professional director of photography for feature films, documentaries, TV shows, or music videos. How do you plan for your shoots? I try to get as much information about the shoot as I can. ï¿½ï¿½I am a big believer in research and approaching each situation as its own unique problems. ï¿½ï¿½Since shoots can vary so much, doing your homework and coming to set with experience is the best way to approach it. Do you do a lot of freelance work around Btown? I do most of my work within student film productions as well as the random music gigs and pictures anyone needs. Who are you most inspired by? I am most inspired by directors and cinematographers who are working now or who have came before me. Anyone with strong aesthetic and creative inventiveness really inspire me. ï¿½ï¿½Directors like PT Anderson, Stanely Kubrick, Chris Marker are great. ï¿½ï¿½The great cinematographers I admire are Sven Nykvist, Emmanuel Lubzeki, and Michael Slovis. Have you shot any other videos for bands? I have not shot for any other bands. ï¿½ï¿½Mighty Bros were my first! You girlfriend will be helping with our shoot in June, whatâ€™s it like sharing the same passion? It is great to have a partner with similar passions for me because we can teach and inspire each other as well as connect on many levels. ï¿½ï¿½We have worked together a handful of times and when we plan properly it is an effective team. ï¿½ï¿½We also do a lot of our work independent from each other. What was your favorite thing about working with Mighty Brother? I like working with Mighty Brother because they are fun guys who have an intimate sound from what I have heard. ï¿½ï¿½Chill group of guys who are understanding and willing to work with me to get the job done. What is your approach to shooting live music? Besides planning, shooting live music is all about getting enough coverage to work with in the edit. Also sound and video synch is KEY. What is your favorite piece of equipment? My favorite piece of equipment in telecom is probably the package of Cine lens that we have from Canon. They are super fast lens that give a great look to what they are capturing. Whereâ€™s the best place to capture an Adam in the wild? The best place to catch me in the wild is on some lonesome trail, be it desert, mountains, ocean, forest. What is your favorite Beer? My favorite beer has to be Evil Twin Bible Belt. ï¿½ï¿½I had it in a craft beer bar in London and I fell in love with it. ï¿½ï¿½After I looked it up I realized that it was brewed only once so I will probably never have it again! If we were to summon you back from the dead, what 3 items would we have to put in a chalk circle? To summon me from the dead you would need a Chipotle burrito bowl done my way, a bottle of the Evil Twin Bible Belt poured onto my grave, and cologne blessed by Aphrodite herself. What are you looking forward to most this summer? This summer I am taking part in a photography program in Japan so that will be amazing. I have a few experimental short films in mind going there. What is the best way to approach you for video shooting/production advice and services? Or the the best way to contact you? The best way to approach me for video work is know what you want out of the finished product. Coming to me with that in mind I can put my skills and resources to better suit the clientâ€™s needs. Same goes with giving advice: know as best as you can the pertinent details. The best way to contact me is through email: adamlee@indiana.edu or adamlee133@gmail.com Are you working on any exciting projects right now? I am working on finishing up a documentary short about Deniz an opera singer who lived in the co-op with me. Trying to fit her personality and talent into a 5-8 minute doc is challenging! Would you recommend us to a friend? I would recommend you guys to friends who are down with the folkly, fun, and connected vibes your music produces. We want to thank everyone again for collaborating with us on this video shoot! Adam Lee, Kyle Houpt, Bryce Ferendo, also Diederik van Wassenaer (The Underhills; Dietrich Jon) for killing it on violin! ï¿½ï¿½ ï¿½ï¿½ ï¿½ï¿½ ï¿½ï¿½ ï¿½ï¿½ ï¿½ï¿½ ï¿½ï¿½ ï¿½ï¿½<3 MB

preprotext: My Journey Back into Retro Gaming Starts Now!. Last week I decided that I wanted to relive my childhood with some old-school video games from the late 80â€²s and early 90â€²s. The first console I ever owned was the original NES so I jumped on the computer, did a little shopping, and within a few days had a pristine console and a few of my favorite games from when I was younger sitting directly in front of me. I was pretty excited too, as it has been nearly two decades since I traded in my NES with more than fifty games for the new Sega Genesis and a single Sonic the Hedgehog game cartridge, and I was dying to see how the games held up over time. Those were the days, werenâ€™t they? When trading in your old games actually made sense. Fun-co-land with their huge newspapers filled with the trade-in costs for any game you could possibly think of under the sun. Remember when you would gladly get rid of your entire video game library for a single game and the newest console?ï¿½ï¿½Donâ€™t worry Iâ€™m not judging you. It had twice the bits! You had no choice. So I sat down and I plugged in the system and after a few minutes of blowing and jiggling on cartridges I was well on my way to playing one of the greatest video games of all time: Super Mario 3. We typically remember things from our childhood as being far greater than they actually are, and itâ€™s usually not until we experience them again as an adult that we realize how truly awful they were to begin with. Fortunately for me Super Mario 3 is not one of these things. Sure it doesnâ€™t have the graphics that these new games have and you can beat it in a few hours if you know what youâ€™re doing, but even without the graphics, the ability to play online, or any of the other bells and whistles that come along with games today, itâ€™s still just as fun as any of them. And thatâ€™s all that matters.ï¿½ï¿½ Games may look a hell of a lot better these days and theyâ€™re definitely capable of doing more than ever before, but no matter what - they will never be more funï¿½ï¿½thanï¿½ï¿½the games most of us enjoyed as children. A fun game is a fun game and no amount of graphics can change that. Donâ€™t believe me? Play this classic and tell me Iâ€™m wrong after youâ€™ve spent five hours trying to free the princess and defeat Bowser in World 8. Go ahead, I dare you. Thereâ€™s been a lot of controversy in the past few years about people dressing up in racially insensitive Halloween costumes. Like black-face, red-face, yellow-face. First off, the only times you should dress up in a racially offensive Halloween costume is if youâ€™re going to dress up as Mickey Rooneyâ€™s character in Breakfast at Tiffanyâ€™s. Or Clarence Thomas or Bobby Jindal because technically theyâ€™re already white. Or if youâ€™re going to dress up as one of the characters from â€œThe Last Airbenderâ€ or every other anime (even though not everyone will guess that youâ€™re *insert obscure character here* but whatever as long as you have fun!) as long as itâ€™s not for the sake of being offensive. Or if youâ€™re going to do a group costume as the Village People and donâ€™t have a Native American friend to be the Native American. Thereâ€™s plenty of offensive costume ideas without putting shoe shine on your face or taping your eyes back. You can still stay in your same race. And this October, Iâ€™m going to give you guys some amazing ideas. So you can still be offensive. My first idea is a twist on one of the sexiest, yet most intelligent First Ladies ever. Along with Eleanor Roosevelt, Hilary Clinton, and Michelle Obama is Jackie Kennedy Onassis. Extremely intelligent, brave, yet at the same time, a fashion symbol. Now, how do we make Jackie O offensive? Dress up as her AFTER the assassination of her husband, John F Kennedy, who was â€œa macho, womanizing stud who conquered the MOON!â€ (if you get the reference, you get a cookie). As we know, when JFK was shot, some of his blood and stuff got on one of Jackieâ€™s infamous pink suits. Which she still wore when his Vice President, LBJ, was sworn in. So, hereâ€™s what you need to remind people of one of the most tragic days in American history. 1. Buy a Jackie Kennedy costume. Thereâ€™s tons of them online. Thereâ€™s this one Which is $29.99. Or, if you have more to splurge, and want something closer to the infamous suit Jackie wore during one of the most tragic days ever: Try this one. Itâ€™s $149.99. 2. Get some fake blood. Ben Nye is my personal favorite. Itâ€™ll be available at pretty much any Halloween or costume store. Be sure that itâ€™s enough for step number 3, when you: 3. Splatter the fake blood on your costume. Donâ€™t go overboard, though. You donâ€™t want to be oozing in it. Just make it look like the love of your life just got shot next to you in an open car. 4. If possible, add something that looks like gore, like grapefruit, and drape it on your shoulder along with a fake eyeball. And bam! Youâ€™re Jackie O. 5. If you want to make it a couple or group costume, get one person to dress up as JFK himself. Simply wear a suit, drape some fake blood on it, cover part of your face in blood, put some chiclets on your shoulder for some teeth, maybe add a fake eyeball, and BAM! Youâ€™re JFK. If you want to make it a group costume, get one of your friends to wear grass-stained pants. If you donâ€™t get what that means, ask your friend who wears tinfoil on his head. Tyler Blackettâ€™s late own goal compromised Manchester Unitedâ€™s hopes of automatic Champions League qualification as Arsenal drew 1-1 at Old Trafford in the Premier League on Sunday. The hosts took the lead when Ashley Young crossed for Ander Herrera to volley home, but Arsene Wengerâ€™s side earned a point in the 82nd minute when Theo Walcottâ€™s shot nicked off Blackett and looped over United substitute goalkeeper Victor Valdes. The result kept Arsenal two points above United in third place in the table and the FA Cup finalists can secure a Champions League group-stage berth by winning at home to Sunderland in their game in hand on Wednesday. Liverpoolâ€™s 3-1 loss to Crystal Palace on Saturday meant that United were already guaranteed at least a place in the Champions League play-off round, which was the minimum requirement when Louis van Gaal took up his post as manager last year. But of more pressing concern is the future of goalkeeper David de Gea, heavily linked with Real Madrid and who may have already made his final United appearance after being forced off by injury in the second half. Arsenal were unchanged for the sixth game running â€“ the first time that has happened since January 1994 â€“ and as has been their approach in recent major showdowns, they were content to let their opponents attack them. It led to a number of half-chances for United, with Young, Radamel Falcao, Chris Smalling â€“ captain in Wayne Rooneyâ€™s absence â€“ and Juan Mata all threatening. A slip at the other end by Phil Jones gave Arsenal a sight of goal, but despite being flat on his front, the United centre-back improvised brilliantly by swiping the ball away from Olivier Giroud with his head. It was United, though, who were making the running, and they took the lead on the half hour. Young stood up a cross from the left flank and with two defenders drawn to the giant Marouane Fellaini, Herrera met the ball flush on the volley at the back post to claim his eighth goal of the season. - Exit Falcao - Arsenal failed to muster a single shot on target in the first half and when Giroudâ€™s knock-down fell kindly for Alexis Sanchez early in the second, the Chilean shanked a shot high into the East Stand. The game was a last chance for Falcao to impress the United fans after a frustrating loan spell from Monaco, but he spent much of the first half on his backside, the victim of a slippery pitch, and gave way for former Arsenal striker Robin van Persie on the hour. The apologetic wave Falcao gave as he left the pitch suggested he will not be seen at Old Trafford again in a United shirt. Giroud, Van Persieâ€™s successor as Arsenalâ€™s attacking figurehead, belatedly got in behind the United defence moments later, but after neatly beating Marcos Rojo to Mesut Ozilâ€™s cross, he was thwarted by De Gea. â€œDavid de Gea, we want you to stay!â€ chorused the Stretford End, betraying their fear that the Spain international is destined for Madrid. When Arsenal did find a way past De Gea, Aaron Ramsey lobbing a shot over him from Sanchezâ€™s pass, Rojo was on hand to hook clear. De Gea had to depart the fray moments later after an awkward landing, enabling the shaven-headed former Barcelona goalkeeper Valdes to come on for his United debut, four months after joining the club. Valdes had not played a first-team game for over a year and his first task was to pick the ball out of the net after Walcottâ€™s shot nicked off fellow substitute Blackett and looped over him. Both sides had chances to win it, but Giroud could only shoot into the side-netting and Van Persie then ballooned over from Fellainiâ€™s knock-down.

Anderson and Broad boost England as New Zealand collapse. Ben Stokes followed up his record-breaking century with two wickets in two balls as England moved closer to a stunning win in the first Test against New Zealand at Lordâ€™s on Monday. At tea on the fifth and final day, New Zealand were 134 for five, needing a further 211 runs to reach their victory target of 345. But, realistically, they now needed to bat through the final session to force a draw and prevent themselves going 1-0 down in this two-match series. However, the gritty BJ Watling was 36 not out and the dashing Corey Anderson 51 not out, with their sixth-wicket stand so far worth 73. New Zealand, who had earlier collapsed to 12 for three, found themselves 61 for five when Stokes, who on Sunday had scored the fastest Test-hundred at Lordâ€™s, off 85 balls, struck twice in his third over. Kane Williamson, who made 132 in the touristsâ€™ first innings, fell for 27 when he guided Stokes to Joe Root in the gully. And next ball New Zealand captain Brendon McCullum played on to a Stokes inswinger. Given a roar by the crowd worthy of Ian Botham or Andrew Flintoff, Stokes, the New Zealand-born son of former Kiwi rugby league international Ged Stokes, who came to England as a 12-year-old, charged in again. But Anderson survived the hat-trick delivery, allowing the ball to pass his stumps. Anderson, in Stokes-like fashion, later pulled the Durham all-rounder for six. Deciding attack was the best form of defence, Anderson completed a 44-ball fifty in which 46 of his runs â€“ 10 fours and a six â€“ came in boundaries. New Zealand were rocked from the very start of their chase, losing both openers for ducks without a run on the board in a match where, for the most part, they had been on top. The second ball of New Zealandâ€™s innings saw Martin Guptill caught in the slips by Gary Ballance off James Anderson. Guptillâ€™s exit left Anderson just one wicket shy of becoming only the 12th bowler and first from England to take 400 Test wickets. And New Zealand were still on nought when Stuart Broadâ€™s first ball of the second over had Tom Latham lbw for a golden duck. For New Zealand, it was all starting to become horribly reminiscent of their last Test at Lordâ€™s, in 2013, when they collapsed to 68 all out chasing 239. Broad, who took a Test-best seven for 44 against New Zealand at Lordâ€™s two years ago, had Ross Taylor plumb lbw for eight after having him dropped on two. Earlier, England were dismissed for 478 after resuming on 429 for six. England captain Alastair Cook took his overnight 153 not out â€“ the left-handed openerâ€™s second Test hundred in as many matches but first on home soil for two years - to 162. But his marathon innings came to an end when he was caught behind off an inside edge to Trent Boult. Cook batted for more than nine hours, facing 345 balls including 17 fours. His innings extended Cookâ€™s England record for most Test hundreds to 27. Cook will now need just 32 runs in the second Test at Headingley to surpass Essex mentor Graham Goochâ€™s England Test runs record of 8,900. Cookâ€™s exit was the start of a Boult burst that saw the left-arm paceman wrap up the innings with four wickets for nine runs in 17 balls. Boultâ€™s final figures of five for 85 saw him gain a coveted place on the Lordâ€™s honours board for the first time in his career.

a few shows i went to. I havenâ€™t been to any shows these last few weeks, but I did got to a couple shows during the break, though none of them really interested me in terms of furthering my practice, but were nice to see at any rate: 1) Christina Mackie at Tate Britian Being interested in different ways to apply or play with paint, I found this to be an interesting installation. What interested me most was the flow of paint through the material and how light the material was and how it absorbed the paint. 2) Richard Long at The Alan Cristea Gallery I found this one interesting on two levels:ï¿½ï¿½ - Iâ€™m not overly familiar with most of Richard Longâ€™s work, though his photograph â€œA Line Made By Walkingâ€ so these works, which are very different different peaked my attention. I think it was mostly nice to see how much a practice can evolve and differ depending on your interest at the time.ï¿½ï¿½ - Also I found the works very evocative. Having just worked on a painting that dealt with a dark colour scheme and an illusionary kinda of landscape these works made me think of dark forests. Gothic forests and ghosts. They has an interesting almost fading sense of time.ï¿½ï¿½ 3) Paul McDevitt at the Stephen Friedman Gallery That these works were done in charcoal really surprised me, because from the poster and at first glance you think they are paintings. Thereâ€™s that call back to Roy Lichtensteinâ€™s brush stroke paintings. So I was prepared to accept them and view them as paintings. That they were drawings changed a lot for me, maybe especially the amount of care that put into making them. I think to draw on this scale (and theyâ€™re quite large works) takes a lot dedication and patience. Things I think I sometimes lack when making work.ï¿½ï¿½ The works were incredibly engaging to view and I think some of my favourite pieces of art Iâ€™ve viewed recently. Mostly I enjoyed the feeling of texture in the works while the medium is very flat.

Each sign of the Zodiac can be divided into three subsections called Decans. Each Decan roughly corresponds to 10 degrees or 10 days of the signs time period. Decans can provide a more detailed account of an individualâ€™s personality traits and character and reveal how people born under the same sign can be very different. The Taurus personality can differ according to which one of the Taurus Decans an individual is born under: First Taurus Decan (April 20 - April 30) This is the first of the Taurus Decans and is ruled by the planet Venus. The first Decan Taurus personality is characterised by determination, stability and sensuality. You are determined to get the things you want form life and will do everything in your power to achieve the goals you set for yourself. PUTRAJAYA, May 14 â€• The Federal Territories Islamic Religious Department (JAWI) and two ministerâ€™s bid to appeal a court ruling favouring Bordersâ€™ Muslim staff Nik Raina Nik Abdul Aziz will likely go on at the Federal Court this August, their lawyer said today. JAWIâ€™s lawyer Shamsul Bolhassan said he had not received any instructions to retract the appeal bid against the Court of Appeal ruling that found JAWI had acted illegally and unconstitutionally by prosecuting Nik Raina. â€œI think we are going to proceed. So far no instructions to withdraw,â€ the senior federal counsel from the Attorney-Generalâ€™s Chambers told Malay Mail Online when met here. Shamsul is also representing the then Home Minister Datuk Seri Hishammuddin Hussein and Minister in charge of Islamic affairs, Datuk Seri Jamil Khir Baharom in this appeal bid. Last December, the Court of Appeal ruled in favour of Nik Raina, stating that JAWIâ€™s prosecution against her simply because she was a Muslim and because it could not charge the company and her non-Muslim supervisor was â€œunreasonable, irrationalâ€ and against the â€œprinciple of fairness and justiceâ€. Despite the Kuala Lumpur High Court and Court of Appeal ruling in Nik Rainaâ€™s favour in her judicial review challenging JAWIâ€™s actions, the Islamic department and the two ministers had this year filed for leave to appeal at the Federal Court. Activists using social media to fight jihadists. MONTREAL - A Montreal-based human rights think-tank wants to fight jihadist groups on their own online turf, saying itâ€™s time to push back against the propaganda. Kyle Matthews, who heads Concordia Universityâ€™s Digital Mass Atrocity Prevention Lab, says the use of social media by groups like the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant to lure young people and promote its cause goes largely unchecked. Groups like ISIL are evidence of the increasing convergence between new technology, atrocities and extremist factions, said Matthews. â€œISIS has become like a genocidal force where it exists and it tends to squash all diversity and annihilate anyone who is different,â€ he said in a recent interview. â€œTied to that, we have cases in Canada where individuals are being radicalized online, targeted on social media much like online sexual predators.â€ The lab was introduced this year and is part of the Montreal Institute for Genocide and Human Rights Studies, where Matthews is deputy director. Montreal has been the focus of much scrutiny after the recent arrest of 10 youths suspected of wanting to join jihadist groups in the Middle East. Their passports were confiscated, although no charges were laid. A local junior college attended by some of those youths noted it was powerless to stop recruitment that largely takes place online. That followed the disappearance in January of several young Quebecers who are believed to have fled to Turkey to eventually join jihadist organizations in the Middle East. Some are thought to have attended the same school. In Quebec, the province is set to introduce anti-radicalization measures in the coming weeks, while the City of Montreal has said it plans to open an anti-radicalization centre. While some people advocate closing down social media accounts and outing jihadist cheerleaders, Matthews said responding to such propaganda and tackling the ideology is equally important. â€œTheyâ€™re creating a narrative that kind of makes the ISIS fighter look like the Che Guevara of 2015,â€ Matthews said. The propaganda videos are professionally produced. Groups like ISIL are also prolific, with thousands of Twitter and Facebook accounts that constantly recruit and target disaffected youth in the West. There have been reports about their use of apps and other programs, like the Russian equivalent of Facebook, to bypass western intelligence. Jihadists have also demonstrated a long reach: an ISIL audio recording in mid-May, purportedly from its reclusive leader, Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, was translated into several languages and shared via some 46,000 Twitter accounts linked to the group. With so much jihadist content available, Matthews said governments and organizations worldwide are struggling to keep up. â€œThe response is so slow and what I keep telling people, the government canâ€™t do this stuff: bureaucrats are not creative, they donâ€™t understand how social media works,â€ Matthews said. â€œThe ideas are where we have to engage if we want to prevent this from getting any worse.â€ Matthews and his team will present ways to deal with digital jihadism at the Deutsche Welle Global Media Forum in Germany in June. The best line of attack, he believes, may lie in a diverse group of untapped sources such as creative filmmakers, tech firms and Muslims who understand the situation and can provide a counterpoint. â€œThey (ISIL) have got an entire social media infrastructure thatâ€™s laid out and theyâ€™re doing it in multiple languages and I donâ€™t see any equivalent response,â€ Matthews said. Programs combating extremism are rare. One program launched in February is called Extreme Dialogue, an educational tool that features testimonial videos and resources to get teens to question views being peddled to them. Among the participants is Christianne Boudreau, a Calgary mother whose 22-year-old son, Damian Clairmont, was killed last year while fighting with jihadists in Syria. She said many youths sympathize with radical groups because they find a sense of belonging and family online. â€œTheyâ€™re being told that all the propaganda (in western media) is all lies â€” my son was told the same thing,â€ Boudreau said, adding many Canadian kids likely sympathize with the movement but have not yet acted upon their feelings. Boudreau also works with families touched by radicalization and notes resources are scarce. â€œUntil we start bonding together and building community resilience and creating those outreach points for people, itâ€™s going to be very difficult to slow this down,â€ she said.

preprotext: Mary Ellen Mark & Youth. The American photographer, Mary Ellen Mark, has passed away at the age of 75. She leaves behind a body a work that continues to shock, intrigue, and enlighten. Though also known for her portraits and advertising photography, Mark was particularly renowned for her photojournalism. She was drawn to the more marginalised figures of society, photographing those who danced upon its fringes. Navy divers to help raise confederate warship artifacts. NORFOLK, Va. (AP) â€” The Navy is preparing to send one if its premier diving teams to Georgia to help salvage a Confederate warship from the depths of the Savannah River. Before it ever fired a shot, the 1,200 ton ironclad CSS Georgia was scuttled by its own crew to prevent its capture by Gen. William T. Sherman when his Union army took Savannah in December 1864. Today, itâ€™s considered a captured enemy vessel and is property of the U.S. Navy. The shipwreck is being removed as part of a $703 million project to deepen the river channel so larger cargo ships can reach the Port of Savannah. Before the harbor can be deepened, the CSS Georgia has to be raised. After years of planning, archaeologists began tagging and recording the locations of thousands of pieces from the shipwreck in January. Theyâ€™ve been able to bring smaller artifacts to the surface, but the Navy is being called in to raise the 120-foot-long shipâ€™s larger sections and weapons. Navy divers are scheduled to arrive at the site near downtown Savannah about 100 yards from the shore on June 1. The Navy divers assigned to the project are from the same unit thatâ€™s had some of the militaryâ€™s highest profile salvage operations. That includes the Civil War ironclad USS Monitor, TWA Flight 800, Swiss Air Flight 111, as well as the space shuttles Challenger and Columbia. Divers from the Virginia Beach-based Mobile Diving Salvage Unit 2 also provided damage assessments and repairs on the USS Cole following the terrorist attack on it in Yemen in 2000 and pulled up wreckage from an F-16 that crashed off the eastern shore of Virginia in 2013. In Georgia, Navy divers will pull up parts of the shipâ€™s armor systems, steam engine components and small structure pieces. Theyâ€™ll eventually be sent to one of the U.S. Naval History and Heritage Commandâ€™s repositories and Conservation Research Laboratory at Texas A&M University in College Station, Texas. â€œThe desire to maintain the ship in somewhat of a conservable state is one of the primary concerns. Thatâ€™s a little bit different from typical salvage. Often times, aside from human remains or things like a flight data recorder, itâ€™s simply object recovery. Itâ€™s bringing it up safely and disposing of it. Whereas these artifacts will be preserved for future generations,â€ said Chief Warrant Officer Jason Potts, the on-scene commander for the CSS Georgia operation. The weapons, which include four cannons and about 50 projectiles that are either rifle shells or cannon balls, will be handled by explosive ordnance disposal technicians from Kings Bay, Georgia. Potts said the weapons systems would be removed first, then divers would focus on the propeller and main shaft, portions of its steam machinery and large portions of the shipâ€™s armored encasement. The armor for the ship, which was anchored off Fort Jackson as a floating gun battery, was made out of railroad iron. Archaeologists will still make sure there are no other remnants remaining after the Navy divers leave at the end of July. Work to preserve and catalog all of the individual artifacts is expected to take another year or more. ___ Brock Vergakis can be reached at www.twitter.com/BrockVergakis
